#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/CosineSimilarity.md:5
msgid "$$ \\frac{\\langle x, y \\rangle}{||x||\\_2 \\cdot ||y||\\_2} = \\cos \\phi $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/CosineSimilarity.md:9
msgid "Orchini similarity"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/CosineSimilarity.md:10
msgid "angular similarity"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/CosineSimilarity.md:11
msgid "normalized dot product"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/CosineSimilarity.md:12
msgid "Ochiai–Otsuka similarity"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/CosineSimilarity.md:13
msgid "TF-IDF similarity"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/CosineSimilarity.md:14
msgid "cosine distance"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/CosineSimilarity.md:15
msgid "Orloci distance"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/CosineSimilarity.md:16
msgid "chord distance"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/CosineSimilarity.md:20
msgid "The cosine similarity is the case $\\bar{x} = \\bar{y} = 0$ of the Pearson correlation similarity, where $\\phi$ is the angle between vectors $x$ and $y$. In the binary case, it becomes $\\frac{|X \\cap Y|}{\\sqrt{|X| \\cdot |Y|}}$ and is called the **Ochiai–Otsuka similarity**. In Record Linkage, it is called **TF-IDF similarity**. The angular semimetric on $\\mathbb{R}^n$ is defined by $\\arccos \\phi$. The **cosine distance** is $1 - \\cos \\phi$, and the **Orloci distance** is $\\sqrt{2(1 - \\cos \\phi)} = \\sqrt{\\sum (\\frac{x_i}{||x||\\_2} - \\frac{y_i}{||y||\\_2})^2}$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/CovarianceSimilarity.md:5
msgid "$$ \\frac{\\sum (x_i - \\bar{x})(y_i - \\bar{y})}{n} = \\frac{\\sum x_i y_i}{n} - \\bar{x} \\cdot \\bar{y} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/CovarianceSimilarity.md:9
msgid "The covariance similarity is a similarity on $\\mathbb{R}^n$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/GlobalCorrelationDistance.md:5
msgid "$$ I(d) = \\frac{n \\sum\\_{1 \\le i \\neq j \\le n} w\\_{ij}(d) (x_i - \\bar{x})(x_j - \\bar{x})}{\\sum\\_{1 \\le i \\neq j \\le n} w\\_{ij}(d) \\sum\\_{1 \\le i \\le n} (x_i - \\bar{x})^2} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/GlobalCorrelationDistance.md:9
msgid "Moran autocorrelation coefficient"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/GlobalCorrelationDistance.md:13
msgid "Let $x \\in \\mathbb{R}^n$ and $(A, d)$ be a metric space with $n$ points $a_1, \\dots, a_n$. For any $d > 0$, the Moran autocorrelation coefficient is defined by the formula above, where the weight $w\\_{ij}(d)$ is $1$ if $d(a_i, a_j) = d$ and $0$, otherwise. The global correlation distance is the least value $d'$ for which $I(d) = 0$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/LogLikelihoodDistance.md:5
msgid "$$ \\sum\\_{x \\in A} x \\log \\frac{x}{|A|} + \\sum\\_{x \\in B} x \\log \\frac{x}{|B|} - \\sum\\_{x \\in A \\cup B} x \\log \\frac{x}{|A \\cup B|} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/LogLikelihoodDistance.md:9
msgid "Given two clusters $A$ and $B$, their log-likelihood distance is the decrease in log-likelihood as they are combined into one cluster."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/MorisitaHornSimilarity.md:5
msgid "$$ \\frac{2 \\langle x, y \\rangle}{||x||\\_2^2 \\cdot \\frac{\\bar{y}}{\\bar{x}} + ||y||\\_2^2 \\cdot \\frac{\\bar{x}}{\\bar{y}}} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/MorisitaHornSimilarity.md:9
msgid "The Morisita–Horn similarity is a similarity on $\\mathbb{R}^n$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/MorisitaHornSimilarity.md:13
msgid "[Morisita, 1959](https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/memsci1950/3/1/3_1_65/_article \"Measuring of interspecific association and similarity between communities\")"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/PearsonCorrelationSimilarity.md:5
msgid "$$ s = \\frac{\\sum (x_i - \\bar{x})(y_i - \\bar{y})}{\\sqrt{\\sum (x_j - \\bar{x})^2 \\sum (y_j - \\bar{y})^2}} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/PearsonCorrelationSimilarity.md:9
msgid "Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/PearsonCorrelationSimilarity.md:10
msgid "Pearson distance"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/PearsonCorrelationSimilarity.md:11
msgid "correlation distance"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/PearsonCorrelationSimilarity.md:15
msgid "The Pearson correlation similarity is a similarity on $\\mathbb{R}^n$. The **Pearson distance** (or correlation distance) is defined by $1 - s = \\frac{1}{2} \\sum \\left( \\frac{x_i - \\bar{x}}{\\sqrt{\\sum (x_j - \\bar{x})^2}} - \\frac{y_i - \\bar{y}}{\\sqrt{\\sum (y_j - \\bar{y})^2}} \\right)^2$. A multivariate generalization is the RV coefficient $RV(X, Y) = \\frac{Covv(X, Y)}{\\sqrt{Covv(X, X) Covv(Y, Y)}}$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/PearsonCorrelationSimilarity.md:19
msgid "[Escoufier, 1973](https://doi.org/10.2307/2529068 \"Le Traitement des Variables Vectorielles\")"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/SimilarityRatio.md:5
msgid "$$ \\frac{\\langle x, y \\rangle}{\\langle x, y \\rangle + ||x - y||\\_2^2} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/SimilarityRatio.md:9
msgid "Kohonen similarity"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/SimilarityRatio.md:10
msgid "Kumar–Hassebrook similarity"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/SimilarityRatio.md:11
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/JaccardSimilarity.md:9
msgid "Tanimoto similarity"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/SimilarityRatio.md:15
msgid "The similarity ratio is a similarity on $\\mathbb{R}^n$. Its binary case is the Tanimoto similarity."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/SpearmanRankCorrelation.md:5
msgid "$$ \\frac{\\sum (a_i - \\bar{a})(b_i - \\bar{b})}{\\sqrt{\\sum (a_j - \\bar{a})^2 \\sum (b_j - \\bar{b})^2}} = 1 - \\frac{6}{n(n^2 - 1)} \\sum (a_i - b_i)^2 $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/SpearmanRankCorrelation.md:9
msgid "Spearman footrule"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/SpearmanRankCorrelation.md:10
msgid "Kendall $\\tau$ rank correlation"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Correlation/SpearmanRankCorrelation.md:14
msgid "If the sequences $x, y \\in \\mathbb{R}^n$ are ranked separately, then the Pearson correlation similarity is approximated by the Spearman $\\rho$ rank correlation, where $n > 1$ and $a_i = \\text{rank}(x_i)$, $b_i = \\text{rank}(y_i)$. The **Spearman footrule** is defined by $1 - \\frac{3}{n^2 - 1} \\sum |x_i - y_i|$. Another correlation similarity for rankings is the **Kendall $\\tau$ rank correlation**: $\\frac{2 \\sum\\_{1 \\le i \\< j \\le n} \\text{sign}(x_i - x_j) \\text{sign}(y_i - y_j)}{n(n - 1)}$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/BaroniUrbaniBuserSimilarity.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/BrayCurtisSimilarity.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/CanberraDistance.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/CzekanowskyDiceDistance.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/CzekanowskySimilarity.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/DiceSimilarity.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/EllenbergSimilarity.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/GleasonSimilarity.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/IntersectionDistance.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/JaccardSimilarity.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/KulczynskiSimilarity_1.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/KulczynskiSimilarity_2.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/MarylandBridgeSimilarity.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/MotykaSimilarity.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/RobertsSimilarity.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/RuzickaSimilarity.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/SimpsonSimilarity.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/SørensenDistance.md:3
msgid "`Numerical`"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/BaroniUrbaniBuserSimilarity.md:5
msgid "$$ \\frac{\\sum \\min{x_i, y_i} + \\sqrt{\\sum \\min{x_i, y_i} \\sum (\\max\\_{1 \\le j \\le n} x_j - \\max{x_i, y_i})}}{\\sum \\max{x_i, y_i} + \\sqrt{\\sum \\min{x_i, y_i} \\sum (\\max\\_{1 \\le j \\le n} x_j - \\max{x_i, y_i})}} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/BaroniUrbaniBuserSimilarity.md:9
msgid "The Baroni–Urbani–Buser similarity is a similarity on $\\mathbb{R}^n$. In the binary case it takes the form $\\frac{|X \\cap Y| + \\sqrt{|X \\cap Y| \\cdot |\\overline{X \\cup Y}|}}{|X \\cup Y| + \\sqrt{|X \\cap Y| \\cdot |\\overline{X \\cup Y}|}}$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/BrayCurtisSimilarity.md:5
msgid "$$ \\frac{2}{n(\\bar{x} + \\bar{y})} \\sum \\min{x_i, y_i} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/BrayCurtisSimilarity.md:9
msgid "Renkonen percentage similarity"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/BrayCurtisSimilarity.md:13
msgid "The Bray–Curtis similarity is a similarity on $\\mathbb{R}^n$. It is called Renkonen percentage similarity if $x, y$ are frequency vectors."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/BrayCurtisSimilarity.md:17
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/CzekanowskyDiceDistance.md:21
msgid "[Bray and Curtis, 1957](https://doi.org/10.2307/1942268 \"An Ordination of the Upland Forest Communities of Southern Wisconsin\")"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/CanberraDistance.md:5
msgid "$$ \\sum \\frac{|x_i - y_i|}{|x_i| + |y_i|} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/CanberraDistance.md:9
msgid "The Canberra distance is a distance on $\\mathbb{R}^n$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/CanberraDistance.md:13
msgid "[Lance and Williams, 1967](https://doi.org/10.1093/comjnl/9.4.373 \"A General Theory of Classificatory Sorting Strategies\")"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/CzekanowskyDiceDistance.md:5
msgid "$$ 1 - \\frac{2|X \\cap Y|}{|X| + |Y|} = \\frac{|X \\Delta Y|}{|X| + |Y|} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/CzekanowskyDiceDistance.md:7
msgid "Abbreviations"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/CzekanowskyDiceDistance.md:9
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/SørensenDistance.md:9
msgid "Bray–Curtis distance"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/CzekanowskyDiceDistance.md:13
msgid "nonmetric coefficient"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/CzekanowskyDiceDistance.md:17
msgid "The Czekanowsky–Dice distance is a near-metric on ${0, 1}^n$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/CzekanowskySimilarity.md:5
msgid "$$ \\frac{\\sum \\min{x_i, y_i}}{\\sum (x_i + y_i)} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/CzekanowskySimilarity.md:9
msgid "The Czekanowsky similarity is a similarity on $\\mathbb{R}^n$. The corresponding **Czekanowsky distance** is defined by $1 - \\frac{\\sum \\min{x_i, y_i}}{\\sum (x_i + y_i)} = \\frac{\\sum |x_i - y_i|}{\\sum (x_i + y_i)}$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/DiceSimilarity.md:5
msgid "$$ \\frac{\\sum x_i y_i}{\\sum x_i^2 + \\sum y_i^2} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/DiceSimilarity.md:9
msgid "The Dice similarity is a similarity on $\\mathbb{R}^n$. The corresponding **Dice distance** is defined by $1 - \\frac{\\sum x_i y_i}{\\sum x_i^2 + \\sum y_i^2} = \\frac{\\sum |x_i - y_i|}{\\sum x_i^2 + \\sum y_i^2}$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/EllenbergSimilarity.md:5
msgid "$$ \\frac{\\sum (x_i + y_i) 1\\_{x_i y_i \\neq 0}}{\\sum (x_i + y_i) (1 + 1\\_{x_i y_i = 0})} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/EllenbergSimilarity.md:9
msgid "The Ellenberg similarity is a similarity on $\\mathbb{R}^n$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/GleasonSimilarity.md:5
msgid "$$ \\frac{\\sum (x_i + y_i) 1\\_{x_i y_i \\neq 0}}{\\sum (x_i + y_i)} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/GleasonSimilarity.md:9
msgid "The Gleason similarity is a similarity on $\\mathbb{R}^n$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/IntersectionDistance.md:5
msgid "$$ 1 - \\frac{\\sum \\min{x_i, y_i}}{\\min{\\sum x_i, \\sum y_i}} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/IntersectionDistance.md:9
msgid "The intersection distance is a distance on $\\mathbb{R}^n$. It becomes $\\frac{1}{2} \\sum |x_i - y_i|$ if $x, y$ are frequency vectors."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/JaccardSimilarity.md:5
msgid "$$ \\frac{\\sum x_i y_i}{\\sum x_i^2 + \\sum y_i^2 - \\sum x_i y_i} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/JaccardSimilarity.md:10
msgid "Tanimoto distance"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/JaccardSimilarity.md:11
msgid "biotope distance"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/JaccardSimilarity.md:15
msgid "The Jaccard similarity of community is a similarity on $\\mathbb{R}^n$. The corresponding **Jaccard distance** is defined by $1 - \\frac{\\sum x_i y_i}{\\sum x_i^2 + \\sum y_i^2 - \\sum x_i y_i} = \\frac{\\sum (x_i - y_i)^2}{\\sum x_i^2 + \\sum y_i^2 - \\sum x_i y_i}$. The binary cases of Jaccard, Ellenberg and Ruzicka similarities coincide; it is called **Tanimoto similarity**: $\\frac{|X \\cap Y|}{|X \\cup Y|}$. The **Tanimoto distance** (or biotope distance) is a distance on ${0, 1}^n$ defined by $1 - \\frac{|X \\cap Y|}{|X \\cup Y|} = \\frac{|X \\Delta Y|}{|X \\cup Y|}$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/JaccardSimilarity.md:19
msgid "[Jaccard, 1908](https://doi.org/10.1007/BF01611216 \"Nouvelles recherches sur la distribution florale\")"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/KulczynskiSimilarity_1.md:5
msgid "$$ \\frac{\\sum \\min{x_i, y_i}}{\\sum |x_i - y_i|} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/KulczynskiSimilarity_1.md:9
msgid "The Kulczynski similarity 1 is a similarity on $\\mathbb{R}^n$. The corresponding **Kulczynski distance** is $\\frac{\\sum |x_i - y_i|}{\\sum \\min{x_i, y_i}}$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/KulczynskiSimilarity_2.md:5
msgid "$$ \\frac{n}{2} \\left( \\frac{1}{\\bar{x}} + \\frac{1}{\\bar{y}} \\right) \\sum \\min{x_i, y_i} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/KulczynskiSimilarity_2.md:9
msgid "The Kulczynski similarity 2 is a similarity on $\\mathbb{R}^n$. In the binary case it coincides with Maryland bridge similarity; its form is $\\frac{|X \\cap Y| \\cdot (|X| + |Y|)}{2|X| \\cdot |Y|} = \\frac{|X \\cap Y|}{2|X|} + \\frac{|X \\cap Y|}{2|Y|}$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/MarylandBridgeSimilarity.md:5
msgid "$$ \\frac{1}{2} \\left( \\frac{\\sum x_i y_i}{\\sum x_i^2} + \\frac{\\sum x_i y_i}{\\sum y_i^2} \\right) $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/MarylandBridgeSimilarity.md:9
msgid "The Maryland Bridge similarity is a similarity on $\\mathbb{R}^n$. The corresponding **Maryland Bridge distance** is defined by $1 - \\frac{1}{2} \\left( \\frac{\\sum x_i y_i}{\\sum x_i^2} + \\frac{\\sum x_i y_i}{\\sum y_i^2} \\right)$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/MarylandBridgeSimilarity.md:13
msgid "[Mirkin and Koonin, 2003](https://doi.org/10.1186/1471-2105-4-2 \"A top-down method for building genome classification trees with linear binary hierarchies\")"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/MotykaSimilarity.md:5
msgid "$$ \\frac{\\sum \\min{x_i, y_i}}{\\sum (x_i + y_i)} = n \\frac{\\sum \\min{x_i, y_i}}{\\bar{x} + \\bar{y}} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/MotykaSimilarity.md:9
msgid "The Motyka similarity is a similarity on $\\mathbb{R}^n$. The corresponding **Motyka distance** is $1 - \\frac{\\sum \\min{x_i, y_i}}{\\sum (x_i + y_i)} = \\frac{\\sum \\max{x_i, y_i}}{\\sum (x_i + y_i)}$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/RobertsSimilarity.md:5
msgid "$$ \\frac{\\sum (x_i + y_i) \\frac{\\min{x_i, y_i}}{\\max{x_i, y_i}}}{\\sum (x_i + y_i)} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/RobertsSimilarity.md:9
msgid "The Roberts similarity is a similarity on $\\mathbb{R}^n$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/RuzickaSimilarity.md:5
msgid "$$ \\frac{\\sum \\min{x_i, y_i}}{\\sum \\max{x_i, y_i}} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/RuzickaSimilarity.md:9
msgid "Soergel distance"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/RuzickaSimilarity.md:10
msgid "Wave–Edges distance"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/RuzickaSimilarity.md:14
msgid "The Ruzicka similarity is a similarity on $\\mathbb{R}^n$. The corresponding **Soergel distance** is defined as $1 - \\frac{\\sum \\min{x_i, y_i}}{\\sum \\max{x_i, y_i}} = \\frac{\\sum |x_i - y_i|}{\\sum \\max{x_i, y_i}}$. It coincides on $\\mathbb{R}\\_{\\ge 0}^n$ with the fuzzy polynucleotide metric. The **Wave–Edges distance** is defined by $\\sum \\left(1 - \\frac{\\min{x_i, y_i}}{\\max{x_i, y_i}}\\right) = \\sum \\frac{|x_i - y_i|}{\\max{x_i, y_i}}$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/SimpsonSimilarity.md:5
msgid "$$ \\frac{\\sum x_i y_i}{\\min{\\sum x_i, \\sum y_i}} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/SimpsonSimilarity.md:9
msgid "overlap similarity"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/SimpsonSimilarity.md:13
msgid "The Simpson similarity is a similarity on $\\mathbb{R}^n$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/SørensenDistance.md:5
msgid "$$ 1 - \\frac{2}{n(\\bar{x} + \\bar{y})} \\sum \\min{x_i, y_i} = \\frac{\\sum |x_i - y_i|}{\\sum (x_i + y_i)} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/SørensenDistance.md:10
msgid "Sørensen similarity"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/SørensenDistance.md:14
msgid "The Sørensen distance is defined on $\\mathbb{R}^n$. The binary cases of Bray–Curtis, Cleason, Czekanowsky and Dice similarities coincide; it is called **Sørensen similarity**: $\\frac{2|X \\cap Y|}{|X \\cup Y| + |X \\cap Y|} = \\frac{2|X \\cap Y|}{|X| + |Y|}$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Numerical/SørensenDistance.md:18
msgid "[Sørensen, 1948](https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/A-method-of-establishing-groups-of-equal-amplitude-S%C3%B8rensen/ \"A method of establishing groups of equal amplitude in plant sociology based on similarity of species content\")"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/BinaryEuclideanDistance.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/ClarkDistance.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/EffectSize.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/HellingerDistance.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/LorentzianDistance.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/MahalanobisDistance.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/MeanCensoredEuclideanDistance.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/MeehlDistance.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/MultiplicativeDistance.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/NormalizedLpDistance.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/PenroseSizeAndShapeDistances.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/PowerPRDistance.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/SymmetricChi_2Distance.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/SymmetricChi_2Measure.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/WeightedEuclideanDistance.md:3
#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/YjhhrMetrics.md:3
msgid "`Relatives`"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/BinaryEuclideanDistance.md:5
msgid "$$ \\sqrt{\\sum (1\\_{x_i > 0} - 1\\_{y_i > 0})^2} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/BinaryEuclideanDistance.md:9
msgid "The binary Euclidean distance is a distance on $\\mathbb{R}^n$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/ClarkDistance.md:5
msgid "$$ \\left( \\frac{1}{n} \\sum \\left( \\frac{x_i - y_i}{|x_i| + |y_i|} \\right)^2 \\right)^{\\frac{1}{2}} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/ClarkDistance.md:9
msgid "The Clark distance is a distance on $\\mathbb{R}^n$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/ClarkDistance.md:13
msgid "[Clark, 1952](https://doi.org/10.2307/1931022 \"An extension of the coefficient of divergence for use with multiple characters\")"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/EffectSize.md:5
msgid "$$ \\frac{\\bar{x} - \\bar{y}}{s} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/EffectSize.md:9
msgid "statistical distance"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/EffectSize.md:10
msgid "standard distance"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/EffectSize.md:14
msgid "Let $\\bar{x}, \\bar{y}$ be the means of samples $x, y$ and let $s^2$ be the pooled variance of both samples. The effect size is defined by the formula above. Its symmetric version $\\frac{|\\bar{x} - \\bar{y}|}{s}$ is called statistical distance or standard distance."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/EffectSize.md:18
msgid "[Johnson and Wichern, 1982](https://www.pearson.com/us/higher-education/program/Johnson-Applied-Multivariate-Statistical-Analysis-6th-Edition/PGM249031.html \"Applied Multivariate Statistical Analysis\")"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/EffectSize.md:19
msgid "[Flury and Riedwyl, 1986](https://doi.org/10.1080/01621459.1986.10478263 \"Standard Distance in Statistics\")"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/HellingerDistance.md:5
msgid "$$ \\sqrt{2 \\sum \\left( \\sqrt{\\frac{x_i}{\\bar{x}}} - \\sqrt{\\frac{y_i}{\\bar{y}}} \\right)^2} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/HellingerDistance.md:9
msgid "Whittaker index of association"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/HellingerDistance.md:13
msgid "The Hellinger distance is a distance on $\\mathbb{R}\\_+^n$. The **Whittaker index of association** is defined by $\\frac{1}{2} \\sum |\\frac{x_i}{\\bar{x}} - \\frac{y_i}{\\bar{y}}|$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/LorentzianDistance.md:5
msgid "$$ \\sum \\ln(1 + |x_i - y_i|) $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/LorentzianDistance.md:9
msgid "The Lorentzian distance is a distance on $\\mathbb{R}^n$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/MahalanobisDistance.md:5
msgid "$$ ||x - y||\\_A = \\sqrt{(x - y) A (x - y)^T} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/MahalanobisDistance.md:9
msgid "quadratic distance"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/MahalanobisDistance.md:10
msgid "directionally weighted distance"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/MahalanobisDistance.md:11
msgid "standardized Euclidean distance"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/MahalanobisDistance.md:12
msgid "normalized Euclidean distance"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/MahalanobisDistance.md:13
msgid "scaled Euclidean distance"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/MahalanobisDistance.md:17
msgid "The Mahalanobis distance is a semimetric on $\\mathbb{R}^n$, where $A$ is a positive-semidefinite matrix. It is a metric if $A$ is positive-definite. Usually, $A = C^{-1}$, where $C$ is a covariance matrix. If $C$ is a diagonal matrix, then $c\\_{ii} = Var(x_i) = Var(y_i) = \\sigma_i^2$ and it holds $||x - y||\\_{C^{-1}} = \\sqrt{\\sum_i \\frac{(x_i - y_i)^2}{\\sigma_i^2}}$, which is called the **standardized Euclidean distance**. The **maximum scaled difference** is defined by $\\max_i \\frac{(x_i - y_i)^2}{\\sigma_i^2}$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/MahalanobisDistance.md:21
msgid "[Mahalanobis, 1936](https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/On-the-generalised-distance-in-statistics-Mahalanobis/ \"On the generalised distance in statistics\")"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/MahalanobisDistance.md:22
msgid "[Maxwell and Buddemeier, 2002](https://doi.org/10.1007/s00442-002-0917-4 \"Maximum scaled difference\")"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/MeanCensoredEuclideanDistance.md:5
msgid "$$ \\sqrt{\\frac{\\sum (x_i - y_i)^2}{\\sum 1\\_{x_i^2 + y_i^2 \\neq 0}}} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/MeanCensoredEuclideanDistance.md:9
msgid "The mean censored Euclidean distance is a distance on $\\mathbb{R}^n$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/MeehlDistance.md:5
msgid "$$ \\sum\\_{1 \\le i \\le n-1} (x_i - y_i - x\\_{i+1} + y\\_{i+1})^2 $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/MeehlDistance.md:9
msgid "Meehl index"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/MeehlDistance.md:13
msgid "The Meehl distance is a distance on $\\mathbb{R}^n$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/MultiplicativeDistance.md:5
msgid "$$ d\\_{MK}(x, y) = -1 + \\prod\\_{i=1}^n (1 + |x_i - y_i|)^{c_i} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/MultiplicativeDistance.md:9
msgid "The multiplicative distance is defined for any $x, y \\in \\mathbb{R}^n$, where $c_1, \\dots, c_n$ are given positive numbers. Another multiplicative distance for $x, y \\in \\mathbb{N}^n$ is $d_Q(x, y) = \\sum\\_{i=1}^n ||l(x_i) - l(y_i)||\\_1$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/MultiplicativeDistance.md:13
msgid "[Mansouri and Khademi, 2014](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.patrec.2014.04.016 \"A new multiplicative distance metric for high-dimensional data\")"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/MultiplicativeDistance.md:14
msgid "[Qureshi, 2015](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.patrec.2015.03.011 \"A novel multiplicative distance metric for numerical data\")"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/NormalizedLpDistance.md:5
msgid "$$ \\frac{||x - y||\\_p}{||x||\\_p + ||y||\\_p} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/NormalizedLpDistance.md:9
msgid "The normalized $l_p$-distance, $1 \\le p \\le \\infty$, is a distance on $\\mathbb{R}^n$. The only integer value $p$ for which it is a metric is $p=2$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/PenroseSizeAndShapeDistances.md:5
msgid "$$ \\sqrt{n} \\sum |x_i - y_i| \\quad \\text{and} \\quad \\sqrt{\\sum ((x_i - \\bar{x}) - (y_i - \\bar{y}))^2} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/PenroseSizeAndShapeDistances.md:9
msgid "mean character distance"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/PenroseSizeAndShapeDistances.md:13
msgid "The Penrose size distance and Penrose shape distance are distances on $\\mathbb{R}^n$. The sum of their squares is the squared Euclidean distance. The **mean character distance** is defined by $\\frac{\\sum |x_i - y_i|}{n}$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/PenroseSizeAndShapeDistances.md:17
msgid "[Czekanowsky, 1909](https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/Zur-Differentialdiagnose-der-Neandertalgruppe-Czekanowski/ \"Zur Differentialdiagnose der Neandertalgruppe\")"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/PowerPRDistance.md:5
msgid "$$ \\left( \\sum\\_{i=1}^n |x_i - y_i|^p \\right)^{\\frac{1}{r}} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/PowerPRDistance.md:9
msgid "fractional $l_p$-distance"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/PowerPRDistance.md:13
msgid "The power $(p, r)$-distance is a distance on $\\mathbb{R}^n$. For $p = r \\ge 1$, it is the $l_p$-metric, including the Euclidean, Manhattan and Chebyshev metrics. The case $(p, r) = (2, 1)$ corresponds to the squared Euclidean distance. The power $(p, r)$-distance with $0 \\< p = r \\< 1$ is called the **fractional $l_p$-distance**. The **ordinal distance** on $\\mathbb{R}^n$ is defined by $\\left( \\sum\\_{i=1}^n |\\sum\\_{1 \\le j \\le i} (x_j - y_j)|^p \\right)^{\\frac{1}{p}}$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/SymmetricChi_2Distance.md:1
msgid "Symmetric $\\chi^2$-distance"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/SymmetricChi_2Distance.md:5
msgid "$$ \\sqrt{\\sum \\frac{\\bar{x} + \\bar{y}}{n(x_i + y_i)} \\left( \\frac{x_i}{\\bar{x}} - \\frac{y_i}{\\bar{y}} \\right)^2} = \\sqrt{\\sum \\frac{\\bar{x} + \\bar{y}}{n(\\bar{x} \\cdot \\bar{y})^2} \\frac{(x_i \\bar{y} - y_i \\bar{x})^2}{x_i + y_i}} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/SymmetricChi_2Distance.md:9
msgid "chi-distance"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/SymmetricChi_2Distance.md:13
msgid "The symmetric $\\chi^2$-distance is a distance on $\\mathbb{R}^n$. It is a weighted Euclidean distance."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/SymmetricChi_2Measure.md:1
msgid "Symmetric $\\chi^2$-measure"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/SymmetricChi_2Measure.md:5
msgid "$$ \\sum \\frac{2}{\\bar{x} \\cdot \\bar{y}} \\frac{(x_i \\bar{y} - y_i \\bar{x})^2}{x_i + y_i} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/SymmetricChi_2Measure.md:9
msgid "The symmetric $\\chi^2$-measure is a distance on $\\mathbb{R}^n$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/WeightedEuclideanDistance.md:5
msgid "$$ \\sqrt{(x - y)^T A (x - y)} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/WeightedEuclideanDistance.md:9
msgid "The general quadratic-form distance on $\\mathbb{R}^n$ is defined by the formula above, where $A$ is a real nonsingular symmetric $n \\times n$ matrix. The weighted Euclidean distance is the case $A = \\text{diag}(a_i)$, $a_i \\neq 0$, i.e., it is $\\sqrt{\\sum a_i(x_i - y_i)^2}$."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/YjhhrMetrics.md:5
msgid "$$ d(X, Y) = (|X \\setminus Y|^p + |Y \\setminus X|^p)^{\\frac{1}{p}} $$"
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/YjhhrMetrics.md:9
msgid "The YJHHR metrics are defined for any $p \\ge 1$ and two finite sets $X, Y$. Another variant is $d'(X, Y) = \\frac{d(X, Y)}{|X \\cup Y|}$ if $|X \\cup Y| > 0$, and $0$ otherwise."
msgstr ""

#: src/Distances/DataAnalysis/Relative/YjhhrMetrics.md:13
msgid "[Yang _et al._, 2016](https://doi.org/10.1093/bioinformatics/btw318 \"A distance metric for sets of biological sequences\")"
